<p>This journal now has its own domain name: <a href="http://www.thedigitalcar.com">http://thedigitalcar.com</a>.

<p><a name="23"></a><A href="#23"><IMG alt="URL for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Friday, February 23,
2001</b> 

<p>John Wiseman went to the Chicago Auto Show, and <a href="http://www.neodesic.com/~wiseman/carshow/">took some pictures</a>.

<p><a name="22"></a><A href="#22"><IMG alt="URL for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Thursday, February 22,
2001</b> 

<p><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/22/technology/22WIRE.html?pagewanted=all">The Web, Without Wires, Wherever</a> (NY Times).
<blockquote>"At the same moment you're filling up your gas tank, why wouldn't you fill up your in-box?" said Mark Goode, chief executive of MobileStar, a leader in the field. </blockquote>	 
<p><a
 href="http://www.code-alarm.com/" 
     >Code Alarm</a> recently announced alliances to <a href="http://www.code-alarm.com/press20.html">deliver 
web-based telematics</a> with <a href="http://www.atroad.com/">@Road</a>, 
to deliver <a href="http://www.code-alarm.com/press21.html">navigation, concierge and emergency services</a> with the <a href="http://www.autoclubofamerica.com/">Auto Club of America</a>. The Auto Club alliance is particularly 
      interesting--is anyone else aligning with user groups to provide 
      telematics services?

<p>Yes, I guess so--<a 
      href="http://wwwa.com/news/041100/page02.htm">AAA announced a telematics company</a> called <a href="http://www.aaaresponse.com/">Response Services Center</a> LLC in April, 2000. Looking at the web site, though, I'm confused. It says "Our customers are business clients, not end users", which indicates they AAA members are <b>not</b> their clientele.

<p><a name="21"></a><A href="#21"><IMG alt="URL for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Wednesday, February 21,
2001</b> 

<p>What is Microsoft's Smart Phone platform, referenced in this <a
 
      href="http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&amp;STORY=/www/story/02-20-2001/0001431467" 
     >Fonix
press release</a>? From that release:

 <blockquote>The Microsoft Smart Phone platform, currently code-named
Stinger, is the software that powers a new generation of color mobile
phones with advanced mobile Internet and personal information
management (PIM) functionality.  Stinger sets a new standard for smart
phone size and functionality, designed specifically to take advantage
of 2.5 and 3G broadband wireless networks and enable a wealth of
services such as secure corporate and web access, email, and
up-to-date PIM.</blockquote>

<ul>
<li><a
 
        href="http://www.microsoft.com/mobile/phones/smartphone/default.asp" 
       >Microsoft's
Smart Phone</a> page.
<li><a
 
        href="http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/press/2000/Jun00/SamsungPR.asp" 
       >Samsung
signs up</a>.
<li><a href="http://www.allnetdevices.com/news/0002/000225sony.htm">So
does Sony</a>.
<li><a href="http://www.ti.com/sc/docs/news/2000/00164.htm">And Texas Instruments</a>.
<li><a
 
        href="http://www.google.com/search?q=Microsoft+Smart.Phone+&amp;hl=en&amp;lr=lang_en&amp;safe=off&amp;start=10&amp;sa=N" 
       >Google
search</a> for "Microsoft Smart.Phone".</li>   
</ul>

<p><a href="http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&amp;STORY=/www/story/02-20-2001/0001431277" 
     >Siemens press release</a> on technology debuts at SAE congress: Tire
Monitoring System (TMS), Closure Force Limitation (CFL) Anti-Pinch Motor
Technology, The Passive Start/Entry (PASE) System, Fingerprint
Identification, and Other Capitalized Technology Marvels, including Quick Scout(R) PDA, personal digital assistant (PDA)-based portable
Telematics system. 

<p><a name="20"></a><A href="#20"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Tuesday, February 20,
2001</b>

<p><a href="http://195.57.225.91/adeca2/centro/inicio.htm">Adeca's
Centro de Servicos Telematicos</a> has a pretty useless telematics site--all 
Flash, no content.

<p><a
 
      href="http://www.theautolink.com/Transcripts/2000/124.htm#124-3" 
     >Transcript</a>
from The American Driver, about Siemens technology for using PDAs like
Palm Pilots as navigation systems.

<p><a name="19"></a><A href="#19"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Monday, February 19,
2001</b> 

<p><a href="http://www.eyeforauto.com">Eyeforauto.com</a> is having
another
<a href="http://www.eyeforauto.com/telematics/">
telematics meeting</a>, this time in Detroit on May 15-16 (<a
 
      href="http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&amp;STORY=/www/story/02-19-2001/0001430307" 
     >Press
release</a>. <a
 
      href="http://www.eyeforauto.com/telematics/program.shtml" 
     >Full program</a>.).

<p><a href="http://www-personal.umich.edu/~pagreen/">Paul Green</a>, a
senior research scientist in the Human Factors Division of UM's
Transportation Research Institute, does research that seems worthwhile
to pay attention to. (He's on a panel on "driver distraction and
assistance" at the Eyeforauto telematics conference, and, I think, the
only panel member who isn't directly employed by the auto makers or suppliers).

<p><a name="16"></a><A href="#16"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Friday, February 16,
2001</b> 

<p><a
 
      href="http://www.eyeforauto.com/index.asp?news=11636" 
     >DaimlerChrysler
pushes for open systems in telematics market at a media event to
introduce "IT Cruiser" technology with Sun Microsystems</a>:
<blockquote>
Mark Moody, a Sun senior Java architect, said ... the auto industry
should be responsible for setting standards, but within those
standards, cars should function almost as generic devices, able to
link to a large number of service providers in a reliable and stable
way.

</blockquote>
<p><a href="http://www.indicast.com/">Indicast</a>, a "voice portal"
company, has licensed <a href="http://www.fonix.com/">Fonix's</a> <a
 
      href="http://www.fonix.com/products/faasttts.html" 
     >Faast
Text-to-speech</a> engine for use in Indicast's individualized news
service. Apparently, Indicast has its own patented <a
 
      href="http://www.indicast.com/natural.html">natural language
interface</a> for voice portals.

<p>ATT's <a
 
      href="http://communicator.research.att.com/research/communicator.html" 
     >DARPA
Communicator Project</a>. <a
 
      href="http://communicator.research.att.com/research/systemFeatures.html" 
     >"You can try our system at the toll-free number 1 877 289 8021."</a>
OK, I try it--a airplane reservation example. It doesn't recognize 
"Kalamazoo,"and when I try to fly out of Chicago, O'Hare, the system 
responds: "We experience technical problems. DMD is dead." Where do I
send flowers?

<p><a name="15"></a><A href="#15"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Thursday, February 15,
2001</b> 

<p><a
 href="http://www.eautoworld.com/" 
     >eAutoWorld.com</a>, taking place in Detroit on April 
      10-12</A>, has a telematics track.

<p><a href="http://www.fujitsu-fme.com/news/press/start.php3">Fujitsu
Europe</a> press releases, including <a
 
      href="http://www.fujitsu-fme.com/news/press/show.php3?arid=254&amp;prid=118" 
     >their
new graphic display controller.

<p><a
 
      href="http://www.oracle.com/ip/deploy/ias/index.html?wireless.html" 
     >Oracle
has a wireless product</a> which they recently display at a "<a
 
      href="http://www.oracle.com/corporate/press/index.html?607956.html" 
     >car
of the future</a>" track at their first "Appsworld Paris." This was a
SMS (short messaging system) emergency notication application.

<p><a name="14"></a><A href="#14"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Wednesday, February 14,
2001</b> 

<p><a
 
      href="http://www.andreaelectronics.com/safeandsound.htm" 
     >Andrea
Electronics Safe and Sound</a> microphone array for in-car use,
demonstrated at Convergence 2000 in October.

<p>A <a href="http://www.cstr.ed.ac.uk/otherinfo.html">speech and
language</a> research list, from the University of Edinburgh's Centre
for Speech Technology Research.


<p><a name="13"></a><A href="#13"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Tuesday, February 13,
2001</b>

<p><a
 
      href="http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2001/01/14/BU181305.DTL" 
     >Another
article about driver distraction while under the influence of
telematics</a>, from the San Francisco Chronicle.


<p><a name="12"></a><A href="#12"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Monday, February 12,
2001</b>

<p><a
 
      href="http://kz.mlive.com/prnewswire/index.ssf?/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=MI2&amp;STORY=/www/story/02-09-2001/0001424497&amp;EDATE=Feb+9,+2001" 
     >Delphi
Enters Licensing Agreement With MLR, LCC To Strengthen Wireless Voice,
Data Import Into Vehicle</a>. (PR Newswire article). 

<blockquote>MLR's patented technology covers basic protocols and
circuitry for cellular data transmission and also covers more advanced
omnimodal technology that affords automated access to wireless
networks operating on different transmission protocols.</blockquote>

<p><a name="9"></a><A href="#9"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Friday, February 9,
2001</b>

<p><a href="http://www.starrec.com/">TEMIC Speech Processing</a>, a
DaimlerChrysler company, which includes a <a
 
      href="http://www.starrec.com/techno/techno2.htm">cute demo of HMM
speech processing</a>. Their <a
 
      href="http://www.starrec.com/products/prod_au.htm" 
     >StarRec Car Speech Dialog
System</a> can be used in the OEM and aftermarkets. It has a memory
that can store a vocabulary of about 300 words (<a
 
      href="http://www.starrec.com/products/download/TM_DB_SDS_PIB.pdf" 
     >data
sheet in PDF format</a>).

<p><a
 
      href="http://michigan.craintech.com/story.mv?story=965778670840792333&amp;back=home.mv" 
     >I/NET
sets up shop in Chicago with Neodesic alumni</a>. Michigan Craintech
picks up the story of our recent office opening. I wish they had
entitled the article "I/NET sets up shop in Chicago to build
conversational interfaces." 

<p><a
 href="http://www.digitaldetroit.org" 
     >Digitial
Detoit</a> is sponsoring <a
 
      href="http://www.digitaldetroit.org/web/newsletter/challenge-info.asp" 
     >a
challenge</a> to come up with a name for "high tech in southeastern
Michigan." Today is the last day.

<p><a
 
      href="http://www.microsoft.com/AUTOMOTIVE/munichAgenda.pdf" 
     >Interesting
agenda</a> (pdf) for the "First Microsoft European Automotive and
Telematic Conference".

<p><a name="7"></a><A href="#7"><IMG alt="URL
 for this day" border=0 src="includes/anchor.gif" ></a> <b>Wednesday, February 7,
2001</b>

<p>Who is <a href="http://www.voxpilot.com">Voxpilot</a>? They just
received $2.5 million in first-round funding, according to
VentureWire. One of the principals is Dr. Richard Reilly, of 
University College Dublin's Biomedical Engineering group. He's apparently
interested in gesture and speech (<a
 
      href="http://www.ucd.ie/~biomed/personnel/richie/richie.html" 
     >his vita</a>).

